{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":54597,"duration_api_ms":54568,"num_turns":5,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"76769e58-1f9f-4b27-9d72-665800f0c699","total_cost_usd":0.32625775,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":35809,"cache_read_input_tokens":102203,"output_tokens":2053,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":35809,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":5,"outputTokens":2053,"cacheReadInputTokens":102203,"cacheCreationInputTokens":35809,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.32625775,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"rulings":[{"amendment_id":"fr-11-fb2ec5ae","decision":"reject","rationale":"The code at fs.rs:3054-3059 already contains an explicit 'Known limitation' comment documenting this exact race condition and stating the long-term fix is for callers to supply plan_hash explicitly. This is conscious, documented design debt — not an overlooked defect. The race window between dispatch and record_task_run_start is narrow, and threading dispatch-time plan hash through every call path is a significant architectural change that exceeds the scope of a targeted amendment. Two of three votes (planner + Reviewer 1) agree this is acknowledged design debt. Reviewer 2's point that 'documented corruption is still a real bug' has philosophical merit, but the amendment process targets overlooked defects, not redesign of acknowledged trade-offs with explicit tracking comments. The issue is discoverable and its fix path is documented; it should be addressed through the normal design-debt remediation process rather than forced through as a final-review amendment."},{"amendment_id":"fr-11-8183a7c6","decision":"accept","rationale":"Confirmed by reading the code. At fs.rs:3071, new entries set snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation to current_snapshot_hash, which is None when no plan has been persisted yet. At fs.rs:2636-2639, safe_plan_hash_backfill treats snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation==None as 'legacy entry' and refuses backfill. This conflates two semantically distinct states: (1) legacy entries with genuinely unknown provenance, and (2) new entries created before the first plan was persisted. For case (2), when the entry is still Running, both plan_hash and snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation are None, and a plan has since been persisted, there is no prior plan version to conflict with — backfill is safe. Reviewer 2's concern about distinguishing legacy from pre-plan entries is mitigated by the Running status check: legacy entries would typically be in terminal states. The acceptance criterion explicitly states 'Lineage entries auto-populate plan_hash from the milestone snapshot when callers omit it' and this edge case (start before plan, complete after plan) is a real coverage gap. Two of three votes (planner + Reviewer 1) support acceptance with confirmed code-level evidence."}],"summary":"Of the two disputed amendments, one is rejected and one is accepted. fr-11-fb2ec5ae (start-time snapshot race) is rejected because the race condition is already explicitly documented as a 'Known limitation' in the code with a stated fix path — this is acknowledged design debt, not an overlooked defect, and the architectural changes required exceed amendment scope. fr-11-8183a7c6 (pre-plan entry backfill) is accepted because it identifies a genuine coverage gap: entries created before any plan is persisted get snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation=None, which the legacy guard then permanently blocks from backfill, even though these entries have known-empty provenance that is safe to upgrade when a plan later arrives and the entry is still Running."},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"d48ceddb-1c92-4238-9a5b-4c1d521b207f"}
